  # County OK’s new overnight accommodation rezone
  
  Split vote follows debate over ‘right kind’ of accommodation
  
  [By Editor Moabtimes](https://www.moabtimes.com/author/editormoabtimes-com/)
  
  on
  December 30, 2021
  
  [By Sophia Fisher](https://www.moabtimes.com/author/By+Sophia+Fisher)
  
  [Facebook](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook "Facebook") [Twitter](https://www.moabtimes.com/#twitter "Twitter") [Email](https://www.moabtimes.com/#email "Email") [Messenger](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook_messenger "Messenger") [Copy Link](https://www.moabtimes.com/#copy_link "Copy Link") [Message](https://www.moabtimes.com/#sms "Message") [Share](https://www.addtoany.com/share#url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.moabtimes.com%2Farticles%2Fcounty-oks-new-overnight-accommodation-rezone%2F&title=County%20OK%E2%80%99s%20new%20overnight%20accommodation%20rezone)
  
  After involved debate, the Grand County Commission in a split 4-3 vote last week approved a new overnight accommodations overlay (OAO) rezone.
  
  ![](https://www.moabtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/52-sky-retreat-1024x683.jpg)Main Street bustles with tourists and hotels. In early 2020, Grand County altered the approval process for new overnight accommodations to greatly restrict — but not ban — future development. File photo
  
  The 40-acre rezone, lying in the county’s far northeast, advances a proposed astronomy retreat that could include up to 16 permanent or semi-permanent lodging units.
  
  Beyond green-lighting the retreat, however, the vote proved a testing ground for the county’s newly-restrictive OAO approval process, which greatly limits — but does not outright ban — new overnight accommodations approvals.
  
  Commissioners weighed a self-avowed aversion to new overnight accommodations against the retreat’s far-flung location, and a desire to show flexibility for certain kinds of accommodations.
  
  “This is a good opportunity to show that we’re capable of saying ‘yes’ to the right kind of overnight accommodation,” said Commissioner Kevin Walker, who voted to approve the rezone.
  
  In 2019, facing a deluge of new hotels and other overnight rentals that outnumbered primary residences by 40%, the county enacted a six-month moratorium on all new overnight accommodation approvals.
  
  As the moratorium expired in early 2020, the commission altered the OAO rezone process to stanch the flow of new overnight accommodations. Rezones became discretionary legislative decisions — meaning they needed approval from the county commission — and even after approval, new overnight accommodations faced tightened design and construction standards.
  
  Importantly, however, the county did not enact a total ban. According to Commission Chair Mary McGann, who helped create the overlay, county staff specified to the state that they would and could approve applications for unique projects that “the county could be proud of.”
  
  “We promised the state it wasn’t going to be a stopgap with no flexibility,” McGann said. “The ordinance would allow for future developments, but only specific ones.”
  
  And in last week’s debate, the commission helped elucidate which applications might still be approved.
  
  For McGann, the Sky Retreat constitutes one of these cases due to its educational focus, small size, and distance from Moab.
  
  Located by Westwater Canyon off Interstate 70, the Sky Retreat would include roughly a dozen overnight units for astronomy enthusiasts. Developers Mike Toomey and Andy Fasig stressed their interest as one of passion, not profit, and mentioned the retreat’s distance from Moab as a natural limit on its impact. The retreat is located over an hour’s drive from Moab, and half that distance from Fruita, Colorado.
  
  This distance spelled another favorable point for Walker and Commissioner Evan Clapper, who pointed out that the Moab Valley’s saturation of overnight accommodations should not necessarily limit their development in farther-flung parts of Grand County.
  
  However, Commissioner Trisha Hedin, who voted against the rezone, said the retreat’s visitors are still likely to visit Moab, providing economic stimulus but contributing to crowding.
  
  “I don’t want you to fall into the trap of thinking there won’t be impacts on Moab,” she said.
  
  For Commission Vice Chair Gabriel Woytek, these impacts were most poignant in Grand County’s still-skewed ratio of overnight accommodations to residential units, which lies at [1.7](https://1.0.0.7/) to 1. While the Sky Retreat’s proposal includes several units of employee housing, it does not go far enough, Woytek said.
  
  Though Woytek said the retreat held great appeal, particularly for its “divergent” form of tourism, he ultimately voted against the rezone. The county, he said, is “not close” to addressing its volume of tourism.
  
  “The general principled approach that this commission has taken so far should be maintained if we really want to give the community a chance to feel secure,” Woytek added.
  
  Finally, debate over the retreat also covered OAO category definitions, with Commissioner Sarah Stock requesting that county staff exclude “glamping” developments from the broader “campground” category. The Sky Retreat, which applied for the campground designation at the recommendation of county staff, could ultimately consist of permanent or semi-permanent structures.
  
  In the final vote, Woytek joined Hedin and Clapper in opposing the rezone, with McGann, Walker, Stock, and Commissioner Jacques Hadler voting in approval.
  
  Just because the commission approved this rezone, Walker said, does not mean they are ready to approve similar proposals in a different location.
  
  “To me, this doesn’t feel like the beginning of a slippery slope,” he said.
  
  _Editor’s Note: In the original version of this article, Woytek was misquoted as saying “violent volume,” rather than simply “volume,” of tourism. The article has been updated to reflect the correct quotation._
  
