  # Public weighs in on overnight lodging addition
  
  Rezone would advance proposed Westwater astronomy retreat
  
  [By Editor Moabtimes](https://www.moabtimes.com/author/editormoabtimes-com/)
  
  on
  December 09, 2021
  
  [By Sophia Fisher](https://www.moabtimes.com/author/By+Sophia+Fisher)
  
  [Facebook](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook "Facebook") [Twitter](https://www.moabtimes.com/#twitter "Twitter") [Email](https://www.moabtimes.com/#email "Email") [Messenger](https://www.moabtimes.com/#facebook_messenger "Messenger") [Copy Link](https://www.moabtimes.com/#copy_link "Copy Link") [Message](https://www.moabtimes.com/#sms "Message") [Share](https://www.addtoany.com/share#url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.moabtimes.com%2Farticles%2Fpublic-weighs-in-on-overnight-lodging-addition%2F&title=Public%20weighs%20in%20on%20overnight%20lodging%20addition)
  
  There may soon be a new spot to stargaze in Grand County.
  
  ![](https://www.moabtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/49-sky-retreat.jpg)This file photo featuring dark skies at Zion — including a streaking meteor from the Perseids — illustrates the value of night skies in southern Utah. Arches and Canyonlands national parks also attract astrophotographers and others who appreciate starry nights. A proposed astronomy retreat for northeastern Grand County could become another star gazer’s paradise in Westwater. Image courtesy of NPS
  
  On Tuesday, the Grand County Commission solicited public comment on a proposed rezone for an astronomy retreat in northeastern Grand County.
  
  If approved, the rezone would apply an overnight accommodations overlay to the hopeful site of the Sky Retreat at Westwater, a small, off-grid development focused on astronomy outreach.
  
  Envisioned by longtime astronomy-outreach professional Mike Toomey, the Sky Retreat aims to “\[combine\] the attributes of a campground with the outreach facets of astronomy observatories and science museums,” according to the rezone application.
  
  At maximum, the retreat would encompass about 20 structures, including roughly 16 guest units, a common building, and two observation areas.
  
  Business partner Andy Fasig, however, emphasized the development could end up much smaller.
  
  “The hope … is to build a very modest retreat,” he said.
  
  In October, the Grand County Planning Commission voted unanimously, 6-0, to forward a positive recommendation for the rezone to the county commission, with one commissioner absent.
  
  Though Fasig said he’s only received positive feedback about the retreat, unexpected delays — not least the COVID-19 pandemic and the county’s February 2019 moratorium on new overnight accommodations — have snarled the planning process, which began in 2019.
  
  “They loved it, and they’re just trying to get out of their own way after putting so many roadblocks in the way,” Fasig said, referring to county government.
  
  Though the overnight-accommodations moratorium expired six months after enactment, county staff are now investigating the effects of such accommodations on the community, as well as potential avenues to ameliorate negative impacts, such as increased pressure on the local housing market.
  
  Early on, there were concerns raised that the moratorium would impact projects well outside of crowded Moab, with former Commissioner Greg Halliday specifically mentioning the Westwater development.
  
  The Sky Retreat’s application emphasizes several factors that they believe will benefit, or minimize impacts on, Moab — the first being its sheer distance from the city. Located in the far northeast of Grand County, the Sky Retreat property lies nearly three hours round-trip from Moab, and only half that time from Fruita, Colorado.
  
  Due to this distance, guest are unlikely to make day trips to Moab, the rezone application asserts.
  
  The retreat also aims to be “self-contained in every way possible,” with a water well already drilled on the property, and the intent to generate all energy from a solar array while providing two units of employee housing.
  
  Though the retreat is not required to build such housing, Fasig said it’s “always” been his and Toomey’s intent to do so.
  
  “\[Toomey\] is not trying to build a resort and be in the business of making money,” Fasig said. “He just wants to create a venue where he can share his love for astronomy and natural sciences.”
  
  Finally, the application asserts the educational retreat will provide “beneficial diversity in recreational opportunities” to Grand County.
  
  “Our take on recreation is a bit more cerebral and observational,” Fasig said. “Rather than ‘conquer’ nature, we’d like to commune with it and observe it.”
  
  The county staff report notes that while the retreat would “not necessarily enhance economic diversification,” it would indeed help broaden recreational opportunities in the county.
  
  Since initial discussions with county officials in 2019, the rezone parcel has been reduced from 160 acres to 40. Beyond that, the plan has changed little.
  
  Even if the county commission gives the go-ahead, however, Fasig said there is no guarantee the retreat will get built, given the project’s limited budget and the “fatiguing” planning process, which has already stretched past two years.
  
  “We’re trying … to celebrate the dark skies and rare natural beauty that is in the county in a way that’s reasonable and has minimal impact,” Fasig said. “If we can do it, it will lead to people appreciating nature and being motivated to protect and preserve the resources, not abuse them.”
  
  
